The 11 roots of unity can be written as

$1, \alpha, \alpha^{2}, \ldots \ldots \ldots \alpha^{10} \quad$ where $\alpha=\overline{\alpha^{10}} \quad \alpha^{2}=\overline{\alpha^{9}} \quad \alpha^{3}=\overline{\alpha^{8}} \quad \alpha^{4}=\overline{\alpha^{7}} \quad \alpha^{5}=\overline{\alpha^{6}}$

Also, sum of 11 roots of unity $=0$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \Rightarrow \quad 1+\alpha+\ldots . \alpha^{10}=0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \operatorname{Re}\left(1+\alpha+\ldots . \alpha^{10}\right)=0 \\
& \Rightarrow \quad 1+2 \operatorname{Re}\left(\alpha+\alpha^{2}+\alpha^{3}+\alpha^{4}+\alpha^{5}\right)=0 \quad\left[\because \operatorname{Re}(\alpha)=\operatorname{Re}\left(\alpha^{10}\right) \text { and so on }\right] \\
& \Rightarrow \quad \operatorname{Re}\left(\alpha+\alpha^{2}+\alpha^{3}+\alpha^{4}+\alpha^{5}\right)=-1 / 2
\end{aligned}
$$

Illustration - 30 If $a=\cos \alpha+i \sin \alpha, b=\cos \beta+i \sin \beta, c=\cos \gamma+i \sin \gamma$ and $\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{a}=1$, then $\cos (\alpha$ $-\beta)+\cos (\beta-\gamma)+\cos (\gamma-\alpha)$ is equal to :
(A) $\frac{3}{2}$
(B) $\quad-\frac{3}{2}$
(C) 0
(D) 1

\title{
SOLUTION : (D)
}

$$
\begin{aligned}
& a=e^{i \alpha} ; b=e^{i \beta} ; c=e^{i \gamma} \\
& \frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{a}=1 \quad \Rightarrow \quad e^{i(\alpha-\beta)}+e^{i(\beta-\gamma)}+e^{i(\gamma-\alpha)}=1
\end{aligned}
$$

Equating the real parts: $\cos (\alpha-\beta)+\cos (\beta-\gamma)+\cos (\gamma-\alpha)=1$

